'''Sir Henry Yule Braddon''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|KBE|size=85%}} (27 April 1863 &ndash; 8 September 1955) was an Australian diplomat, businessman and [[rugby union]] player who played for [[Otago Rugby Football Union|Otago]], [[New South Wales Rugby Union|New South Wales]] and [[All Blacks|New Zealand]]. The position he generally played in was [[Fullback (rugby union)|fullback]]. He is listed as the second [[All Black]] in playing order.<ref name="AB profile">{{cite web| url = http://stats.allblacks.com/asp/Profile.asp?ABID=81 |title = Henry Braddon | last = Luxford | first = Bob | publisher = New Zealand Rugby Union | accessdate = 16 September 2014}}</ref>

==Biography==
He was born on 27 April 1863 in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], India to [[premier of Tasmania]], [[Edward Braddon|Sir Edward Braddon]]. He moved to [[Invercargill]] in 1882 on transfer with the [[Bank of Australasia]]. He played his club rugby for [[Invercargill Rugby Club (Blues)|Invercargill Rugby Club]] but his provincial rugby for [[Otago Rugby Football Union|Otago]] as the Invercargill-centred [[Southland Rugby Football Union]] did not split away from Otago until 1887. He was selected for the first New Zealand international team, and played in seven of the eight games in Australia in 1884 and is recognised as an Otago's first All Black despite playing in Invercargill at the time of his selection. Braddon later played for [[New South Wales Waratahs|New South Wales]] from 1888 until 1892.<ref name="AB profile"/>

Braddon had a commercial and political career in Australia, working for Dalgetys and representing Australia as Commonwealth Commissioner in the United States. He was appointed a member of the [[New South Wales Legislative Council]] in 1917 and was an elected member of that body from 1934 to 1940.<ref name="ADB profile">{{cite web |url= http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/braddon-sir-henry-yule-143 |title=Braddon, Sir Henry Yule (1863–1955) |date=1979 |website=Australian Dictionary of Biography |publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University |accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> He was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1920,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32090 |date=19 October 1920 |page=10095 }}</ref> and died in the Sydney suburb of [[Woollahra, New South Wales|Woollahra]] in 1955.<ref name="ADB profile"/>

==Legacy==
Following the death of [[Henry Roberts (rugby union)|Henry Roberts]] in 1949, Braddon held the distinction of being the oldest living All Black.

